"Giorgi F., Im E.-S., Coppola E., Diffenbaugh N.S., Gao X.J., Mariotti L., Shi Y.","Higher hydroclimatic intensity with global warming",2011,"Journal of Climate","24","20",,"5309","5324",,,10.1175/2011JCLI3979.1,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-80755175224&partnerID=40&md5=2704d7f1a91f51ca3fd38fb38c516e2b","Earth System Physics Section, International Centre for Theoretical Physics, Trieste, Italy; Department of Environmental Earth System Science, Woods Institute for the Environment, Stanford University, Stanford, CA, United States; National Climate Center, Chinese Meteorological Administration, Beijing, China; Earth System Physics Section, International Centre for Theoretical Physics, Trieste, Italy; National Climate Center, Chinese Meteorological Administration, Beijing, China","Giorgi, F., Earth System Physics Section, International Centre for Theoretical Physics, Trieste, Italy; Im, E.-S., Earth System Physics Section, International Centre for Theoretical Physics, Trieste, Italy; Coppola, E., Earth System Physics Section, International Centre for Theoretical Physics, Trieste, Italy; Diffenbaugh, N.S., Department of Environmental Earth System Science, Woods Institute for the Environment, Stanford University, Stanford, CA, United States; Gao, X.J., National Climate Center, Chinese Meteorological Administration, Beijing, China; Mariotti, L., Earth System Physics Section, International Centre for Theoretical Physics, Trieste, Italy; Shi, Y., National Climate Center, Chinese Meteorological Administration, Beijing, China","Because of their dependence on water, natural and human systems are highly sensitive to changes in the hydrologic cycle. The authors introduce a new measure of hydroclimatic intensity (HY-INT), which integrates metrics of precipitation intensity and dry spell length, viewing the response of these two metrics to global warming as deeply interconnected. Using a suite of global and regional climate model experiments, it is found that increasing HY-INT is a consistent and ubiquitous signature of twenty-first-century, greenhouse gas- induced global warming. Depending on the region, the increase in HY-INT is due to an increase in precipitation intensity, dry spell length, or both. Late twentieth-century observations also exhibit dominant positive HY-INT trends, providing a hydroclimatic signature of late twentieth-century warming. The authors find that increasing HY-INT is physically consistent with the response of both precipitation intensity and dry spell length to global warming. Precipitation intensity increases because of increased atmospheric water holding capacity. However, increases in mean precipitation are tied to increases in surface evaporation rates, which are lower than for atmospheric moisture. This leads to a reduction in the number of wet days and an increase in dry spell length. This analysis identifies increasing hydroclimatic intensity as a robust integrated response to global warming, implying increasing risks for systems that are sensitive to wet and dry extremes and providing a potential target for detection and attribution of hydroclimatic changes. © 2011 American Meteorological Society.","Climate variability; Global warming; Hydrology","Atmospheric moisture; Atmospheric water; Climate variability; Dry spells; Highly sensitive; Human system; Hydroclimatic; Hydrologic cycles; Integrated response; Mean precipitation; Precipitation intensity; Regional climate models; Surface evaporation; Wet and dry; Climate models; Climatology; Drought; Greenhouse gases; Global warming; atmospheric moisture; climate modeling; climate variation; global climate; global warming; greenhouse gas; hydrological cycle; precipitation intensity; regional climate",,,,,,"Allan, R.P., Soden, B.J., Atmospheric warming and the amplification of precipitation extremes (2008) Science, 321, pp. 1481-1484; Allen, M.R., Ingram, W.J., Constraints on the future changes in climate and the hydrological cycle (2002) Na